<TITLE> One more sentenced to death for 1993 Mumbai bombs </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MUMBAI, July 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - An Indian court sentenced on Wednesday a Muslim man to die over the country's worst bombings, making him the eleventh person to be condemned to death for planting explosives in India's financial capital in 1993. At least 257 people were killed in 13 blasts at several Mumbai landmarks, including the main stock exchange, a popular cinema and two crowded markets. Mohammed Farooq Pawale was found guilty of leaving two cars packed with high explosives at separate places that killed 24 people. "There cannot be any other sentence which is adequate but death," judge PD Kode said. The death sentences have to be ratified by the Supreme Court. The bombings, police say, were carried out at the behest of India's most wanted man, Muslim gangster Dawood Ibrahim, to avenge the destruction of an ancient mosque by Hindu zealots in 1992 and subsequent riots in which many Muslims were killed. The special anti-terrorism court convicted 100 people in the attacks after a nearly 14-year trial ended last year. It has so far punished 92 of them, mostly with varying jail terms and fines for crimes such as conspiracy, abetment and illegal possession of arms. Those sentenced so far include smugglers, petty criminals and a Bollywood producer, as well as policemen and customs officials who took bribes to let the explosives throu
